{{Infobox church | name = Church of St. Nicholas | fullname = | other name = | native_name = {{lang-hr|Crkva svetog Nikole}} | native_name_lang = | image = Church of St. Nicholas in Nin - by Pudelek.jpg | imagesize = | imagelink = | imagealt = | landscape = | caption = | location = [[Nin, Croatia|Nin]] | country = {{flag|Croatia}} | denomination = [[Roman Catholic]] | status = | functional status = Active | architect = | architectural type = | style = [[Pre-Romanesque art and architecture|Pre-Romanesque]] | years built = 12th century AD | groundbreaking = | completed date = | construction cost = | closed date = | demolished date = | capacity = | length = {{convert|5.90|m|in}} | width = {{convert|5.70|m|in}} | height = {{convert|6|m|in}} | spire quantity = | spire height = | materials = Stone | parish = | deanery = | archdeaconry = | episcopalarea = | archdiocese = [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Zadar|Zadar]] | metropolis = | diocese = | province = | presbytery = | priest = }}
'''Church of St. Nicholas''' ({{lang-hr|Crkva svetog Nikole}}) is a [[Pre-Romanesque art and architecture|Pre-Romanesque]] style Roman Catholic church located in the field of Prehulje, one mile from [[Zadar]], between [[Zaton, Zadar County|Zaton]] and [[Nin, Croatia|Nin]]. It was built on the earthen pyramid mound on top of the [[Liburnians|Liburnian]] prehistoric tomb. The church is the only surviving example of early Romanesque architecture in all of [[Dalmatia]]. It was built at the beginning of the 12th century and is dedicated to [[Saint Nicholas]].
==Description== Church of St. Nicholas was built in form of a fortress. It has a [[Trefoil|trefoil plan]] with four branches arranged around a central circular core, three of which form the apse, and the fourth the input branch. Its dome-shaped vault is reinforced with circular-ribbed arches above which 8 small towers with battlement as a lookout were built in the 16th or 17th century during [[Hundred Years' Croatian–Ottoman War]]. Flanges that are resting on pilasters that are abutting onto the pylons between the apses are placed under the dome. Input branch is rectangular and roofed with a [[mezzanine]] leaning on squinch, while three other branches of semicircular conch are translated with semi calotte. The church was built of small stones and has a smooth outer surface. It has very small dimensions; ''length'': 5.90m, ''width'': 5.70m, ''height''= 6m.<ref>Crkveno graditeljstvo u sjeverozapadnom dijelu zadarskog zaleđa, Građevinar 61 (2009) 7, p. 681</ref>
==Visit of Priul in 1603== In 1603, Church of St. Nicholas was visited by Priul who found neatly kept [[Glagolitic alphabet|Glagolitic]] registers of baptisms and marriages, as well as two Glagolitic [[missal]]s. At the time of his visit, ''Brotherhood of the Holy Spirit'' with 28 members was active in the parish. Priul ordered brotherhood to write its rules that had to be approved by the local bishop.<ref>Amos R. Filipi, Radovi JAZU Zadar,13-14/1968. p. 231-235.</ref>
==Usage== Since the Church was constructed, Mass was celebrated in it on the feast of St. Nicholas on December 6. In recent times, Mass is celebrated on the day of [[Mark the Evangelist|Saint Mark]] on April 25.
